Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The existing research landscape reveals a growing interest in cross-modal and data-efficient hate speech detection, particularly through few-shot learning paradigms. Paper 1 demonstrates that text-based demonstrations can effectively transfer knowledge to vision-language tasks, suggesting that textual representations may encode more generalizable semantic signals of hate. However, this raises a critical question: *Why* do text-only support sets outperform multimodal ones in few-shot settings? Is it due to noise in visual modalities, misalignment between image and language in memes, or the superior expressiveness of linguistic hate markers? Moreover, Papers 2 and 3 highlight the fragility of zero-shot transfer and the importance of contextual understanding—especially for implicit hate—and suggest that model interpretability and layer-wise analysis can reveal meaningful patterns. Building on these insights, I propose a novel investigation that moves beyond performance comparison to *diagnose the representational dynamics* across modalities in few-shot in-context learning. Rather than simply asking which support set performs better, we ask: *How do different modalities contribute to latent space organization during inference, and can we leverage this to design adaptive, modality-weighted prompts?* This idea introduces a diagnostic and generative framework—grounded in probing, alignment metrics, and dynamic prompting—that is absent in prior work. It shifts from empirical observation to mechanistic explanation and optimization, offering both theoretical insight and practical improvement.

